40 2021-03-07 fainting, loss of consciousness Loss of consciousness Client was said to have  passed out while sitting at the waiting area about ... Read more
Close
Loss of consciousness Client was said to have  passed out while sitting at the waiting area about 5 minutes after vaccination. He was brought to the First Aid area  on a wheelchair. Client was noted to having urinary incontinence immediately he arrived at the First Aid area. His head was repositioned and ice pack applied to his forehead and client  recuperated and started talking. Duration of witnessed episode lasted for 15 seconds . Patient claimed having similar episodes with last episode occurring 6 years ago while at work. Vital signs was taken, monitored for  additional 30 minutes and was driven home by his significant other. Vital signs recorded Temp: 96.9deg. F; BP: 102/62 MAP: 76; H.Rate: 78; Oxygen sat: 97%.  (Vasovagal syncope). Neurologic: Loss of consciousness (Comment: Patient had Vasovagal reaction with patient having urinary incontinence, lasting for 15 seconds 5 minutes after vaccination. Patient claimed having similar episodes 6 years ago. )

40 2021-04-02 lightheadedness Patient came in to the clinic to receive his dose of the Janssen COVID vaccine. Within the 15 minute... Read more
Close
Patient came in to the clinic to receive his dose of the Janssen COVID vaccine. Within the 15 minute post-vaccine period, the patient reported feeling warm, sweaty, having clammy hands, and the feeling of almost "passing out". Patient was taken to a patient room to rest, vitals were taken at 13:16 PM with readings of BP: 91/57, HR 72, SpO2 98%, temp 98.5. Patient denies any past medical history, reports he only takes vitamin supplements, and denies any past history of anxiety. He denied any chest pain or SOB. Patient was provided water and was told to rest for a few minutes. Vitals at 1:42 PM were noted to be: BP 108/71, HR 72, SpO2 99%, and temp of 98.1. He says he feels much better and denies any symptoms at this time. ER precautions were given to the patient Called patient again 4/2/21 at 09:59 AM - pt denies any ER visits, hospitalizations, or any visit to any other healthcare provider since his vaccine. The day after his vaccine, he says he developed a headache with left arm soreness (injection site was left upper arm) which was all improved by Monday, 3/22/2020. He says he took Advil, drank plenty of fluids, and rested for his symptoms of headache and arm soreness. He denies any other symptoms of near syncope after his near syncopal episode at the clinic. He denies any symptoms of fevers, CP, SOB, swelling, drainage, or pain at injection site, abdominal pain, dizziness, lightheadedness, or any other side effects/averse effects of the vaccine. He says he is doing well overall
40 2021-04-06 pallor, loss of consciousness Approximately seven minutes after the patient received the Janssen COVID vaccine, he had called out ... Read more
Close
Approximately seven minutes after the patient received the Janssen COVID vaccine, he had called out to his wife/pharmacy technician at the pharmacy stating he did not feel well. His head had fallen back and his eyes were starting to roll back into his head. Patient had saliva starting to foam at the corner of his mouth and it appeared to be the onset of a mild seizure (per wife, patient has had seizure once before after a head injury) and he was turning very pale. Patient seemed to be unresponsive at that time - not answering to questions. At this point, one of the pharmacists ran to the clinic to get help and the other pharmacist administered an Epi-pen to patient's thigh. Patient immediately came around after the injection, looked up and began talking. Staff called 911 and patient was monitored by pharmacy and clinic staff. When the paramedics arrived, the patient was doing better and was able to ride home with his wife.

40 2021-04-08 loss of consciousness, pallor Approximately 5 minutes after the patient received his vaccination, he rested his head on the wall b... Read more
Close
Approximately 5 minutes after the patient received his vaccination, he rested his head on the wall behind him in the chair he was being observed in and passed out and turned white. His wife began slapping his face and screaming his name and the observer called for me. I arrived within seconds and assisted his wife in moving him from the floor to the chair. Within seconds of getting his head to the ground safely, he came back to and was very sweaty, red in the face. He stayed on the ground laying down, and then sitting for approximately 25 minutes. During that time, he told us that he had previously passed out during 3 procedures done at doctors offices. We got him an ice pack and a orange pop as he was complaining of being hot and having only eaten a granola bar all day. He was able to get up to a chair and sat there for an additional 5 minutes, before he was able to walk out on his own accord. I have spoken with the patient twice since, once last evening and once today and he reports he feels great now besides the expected body aches from the vaccination.

40 2021-04-19 chest pain Unusual exhaustion within an hour of the vaccine. Had to go to bed and slept into the evening devel... Read more
Close
Unusual exhaustion within an hour of the vaccine. Had to go to bed and slept into the evening developing a fever of 103, severe thirst and chills. The fever lasted until 10:00 a.m. the following day, but weakness, thirst, chills and body aches continued for 3 more days intermittently. I would feel like I could finally exercise and then be too weak and tired to go back to routine. My appetite declined for 4 to 5 days as food didn't taste appealing. On Thursday, April 8, I announced to my mom in the morning that I finally felt like I was back at almost 100% and later in the afternoon felt nauseous, incredible pain in my chest and had dry heaves. I finally vomited some and was once again overcome by a fever of 101 and all I could do was sleep from severe exhaustion. I am against medication, but finally agreed to taking ibuprofen and tums. After sleeping into the next day around noon, I finally was able to eat some breakfast but the pain in my chest continued and I could rid it for another day. I intermittently had to sleep and gave up my exercise routine until my body has had time to recuperate. I have not fully recovered, but my appetite is picking up. I still require more sleep than normal.

40 2021-04-20 chest pain Pain in chest and back began on Wednesday 4/14. What started out feeling like an uncomfortable pull... Read more
Close
Pain in chest and back began on Wednesday 4/14. What started out feeling like an uncomfortable pulled muscle in my back/chest area on Wednesday escalated rapidly to very sharp stabbing pains in my chest and back by Thursday afternoon 4/15. After discussing my symptoms with the office of my PCP Thursday afternoon, I was told to go to the Emergency Room for evaluation. I checked into the ER at approx 6pm that Thursday evening on 4/15. While there I underwent a blood test, EKG and a chest Xray. Upon evaluating the results of each test the Dr on assignment stated that there were no problems with major organs but could not diagnose. Small red marks began developing on the right side of my chest that same day and progressively expanded in quantity across the right side of my chest and back. A follow-up visit with my PCP was completed on Tuesday 4/20 and the diagnosis of Shingles was confirmed. Pain has not subsided and has only gotten worse as of 4/21. Prescription treatments began the evening of 4/20.

The following day and lasting until present (4/27/2021) I have continued to experience tingling at night, extending to my arm and fingers, random very sharp pains in my chest, and some feeling of strong heart throbbing. Also, I have tested regularly for COVID-19 since my companyconducts covid-19 testing and I have not been infected with COVID-19 at any point during the past year. The continuation of these symptoms is concerning. There have been at least two instances where the sharp pains in my chest were much more intense than the other chest pains I have felt since the vaccine.

51 2021-05-08 arrhythmia Patient initially presented with meningitis-like syndrome with altered mentation, fever, headache, n... Read more
Close
Patient initially presented with meningitis-like syndrome with altered mentation, fever, headache, neck stiffness and found to have multifocal brain (predominantly brainstem lesions). He was initially started on empiric meningitis coverage (ceftriaxone, vanc, ampicillin, acyclovir) which was stopped when CSF tests/cultures returned negative and he improved. Around 10 days later he then developed Guillain-Barre syndrome with ascending weakness of legs and inflammation of cauda equina nerve roots and inflammatory involvement of spinal cord as well causing weakness, numbness, autonomic dysfunction (cardiac arrhythmias) and urinary retention. He was treated with 5 day course of IVIG and improved enough to go to acute rehab. Diagnosis was ultimately concluded as atypical Bickerstaff's encephalitis or idiopathic inflammation of the brain, spinal cord and nerve roots without no other causative event identified other than recent vaccination

Client started to regain color, and report that he was feeling better. Granola bar offered and client ate. Wife reported that this is a common event for client, when having blood drawn, IVs started, or injections given. Client states that he has "passed out many times before." Wife to drive home and stay with husband for the rest of the day. Discussed s/s of allergic reaction, and other s/s that require immediate medical attention. Wife and client verbalized understanding.
